        "trailText":"US magazine Mental Floss succeeds where others have failed by securing interview with notoriously private Bill Watterson",
        "headline":"Calvin and Hobbes' reclusive creator gives rare interview",
        "body":"<p>The American magazine Mental Floss warmed the hearts of comics fans on Thursday when it announced that it had succeeded where so many others have failed: <a href=\"http://mentalfloss.com/article/53216/mental-floss-exclusive-our-interview-bill-watterson#ixzz2hzMknayX\">securing an interview with Bill Watterson</a>, the reclusive creator of the comic strip Calvin and Hobbes.&nbsp;</p> <p>It was only the second known interview with Watterson since he ended his popular strip in 1995. In the years since, Watterson retreated to a private life in north-east Ohio, where has carefully guarded the rights to his creation, refusing to license them or revisit them creatively. His contact with the outside world has been so rare, the magazine's editors told the Poynter Institute, <a href=\"http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/mediawire/226212/mental-floss-editor-no-idea-why-bill-watterson-agreed-to-interview/\">that they put two fact-checkers on the case </a>to be absolutely sure they were talking to the real Bill Watterson.</p> <p>In the interview, part of a feature on the strip scheduled for their December issue, reporter&nbsp;Jake Rossen&nbsp;asks Watterson to put a few rumors to rest: no, there will never be a Calvin and Hobbes movie; and no, he did not actually burn a pile of Hobbes dolls sent to him by an over-enthusiastic stuffed animal manufacturer. He seems wary of the digital world, and of comics' place in it:&nbsp;</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p><strong>Where do you think the comic strip fits in today’s culture?</strong><br />Personally, I like paper and ink better than glowing pixels, but to each his own. Obviously the role of comics is changing very fast. On the one hand, I don’t think comics have ever been more widely accepted or taken as seriously as they are now. On the other hand, the mass media is disintegrating, and audiences are atomizing. I suspect comics will have less widespread cultural impact and make a lot less money. I’m old enough to find all this unsettling, but the world moves on.</p> </blockquote> <p>Over the years, reporters and fans have tried repeatedly to speak with Watterson. In 2003, a reporter <a href=\"http://www.clevescene.com/cleveland/missing/Content?oid=1484634%20%20\">for the Cleveland Scene</a>&nbsp;wrote about his trip to Chagrin Falls, Ohio, and his encounter with a man he thought might have been Watterson. A few years after that, Washington Post journalist Gene Weingarten&nbsp;<a href=\"http://dailycollegian.com/2010/11/08/gene-weingarten-to-discuss-pulitzer-past-with-umass-tues/\">told a story</a> about his own visit to Chagrin Falls, waiting in a hotel on the off chance the artist would agree to meet with him. The next day, around noon, the phone rang, but it wasn’t Watterson. It was Watterson’s agent. “He told me: ‘Bill won’t talk,'&quot; Weingarten said.</p> <p>It was only on the 15th anniversary of the final Calvin and Hobbes strip that the Cleveland Plain-Dealer <a href=\"http://www.cleveland.com/living/index.ssf/2010/02/bill_watterson_creator_of_belo.html\">succeeded in getting Watterson to talk</a>. As he did with Mental Floss, Watterson told the paper then he was still at peace with is decision to go out on top:&nbsp;</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>It's always better to leave the party early. If I had rolled along with the strip's popularity and repeated myself for another five, 10 or 20 years, the people now grieving for Calvin and Hobbes would be wishing me dead and cursing newspapers for running tedious, ancient strips like mine instead of acquiring fresher, livelier talent. And I'd be agreeing with them.</p> </blockquote> <p>The makers of the 2013 documentary Dear Mr Watterson, which features artists talking about the debt they owe to him, were likewise unsuccessful in their attempt to get Watterson to talk about his work.&nbsp;</p> <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KtmV7-f_j7Y\"> <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"345\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/KtmV7-f_j7Y?wmode=opaque&amp;feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"\"></iframe> </figure><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420279965|2013-10-18T10:23:07Z|d0944b7fd9f1e13837e94b312c58ef15054723d8 -->",
