      "id":"books/2013/oct/17/review-maximum-ride-nevermore-james-patterson",
      "sectionId":"books",
      "sectionName":"Books",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-17T14:00:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Maximum Ride: Nevermore by James Patterson - review",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/oct/17/review-maximum-ride-nevermore-james-patterson",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2013/oct/17/review-maximum-ride-nevermore-james-patterson",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p><strong>DavidTennantFan23:</strong> 'I think that the Maximum Ride book series is another gem that I am surprised it is not very well known'</p>",
        "headline":"Maximum Ride: Nevermore by James Patterson - review",
        "body":"<p>Are you prepared to be blown away? Because this is it, the final chapter, and the end has finally come for Maximum Ride and the Flock.</p><p>Max has fought, she has lead, she has loved... but is she ready to finally carry out her destiny? The finale is here- and it's definitely like nothing you've ever read. </p><p>As the Apocalypse grows nearer and nearer, the flock grow closer together. All their lives they have prepared for this, and step by step they have grown stronger. But is this threat too big for even the flock to handle? Will Max choose her perfect other half, Dylan, or her best flock member, Fang? And when the end finally comes, will they truly be able to save the world?</p><p>After seven books building up to this last adventure, this book gives the answers to the deepest secrets of Max's life, and does not disappoint. The puzzle pieces of Max's life finally begin to fit together, and yet more shocks are revealed, which will make you gasp all the way along whilst reading. This book will make you laugh, cry and smile all the way through.</p><p>I really liked this story, and I think that the Maximum Ride book series is another gem that I am surprised it is not very well known. I think this book series is worthy of being as famous as the Twilight saga or The Hunger Games.</p><p>However, I found that at the end this story had not truly satisfied me. I felt the book series, after so many adventures, had not ended quite the way I felt it should - like a hole that wasn't quite filled to the brim. But apart from that, I felt this story had a brilliant story line, truly memorable characters, and a plot that blew me away. Oh Maximum Ride, why did you leave me? How shall I cope...?! </p><p>I would recommend this book to anyone who likes action-packed, funny, and even a little romantic books; readers who have perhaps read stories like The Hunger Games and are looking for more. I found the books very cinematic, as action-packed as any great thriller movie, and I would also recommend it to anyone who perhaps prefers films to books. This book is impossible to put down, and is very addictive. It combines comedy, thriller, romance and fantasy together in a perfect mixture, making it suitable for all types of readers. Without giving too much away, lets just say that if you have been with Maximum Ride the whole journey, you're in for quite a shock when you read this one...</p><p><strong>Want to tell the world about a book you've read? <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">Join the site</a> and send us your review!</strong></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419614622|2013-10-18T10:23:07Z|7fce7f7a90312655c7b68d5014a8cad94f46d7ba -->",
